.ti 0
1  Introduction

The Request For Bikeshed series is a precise, verbose, and a serious joke for members within the Hacklab community. The Bikeshed Authority, an authority of which is in a constant state of colour-based flux, is responsible for the maintenance of the RFB series.

.ti 0
1.1  Terminology

Bikeshedding            Defined as democracy in action or an exercise
.ti 27
in futility.

Dropped Issue           The state of a dispute when the original 
.ti 27
parties can no longer decide what colour of
.ti 27
paint to use.

The key words "MUST", "MUST NOT", "REQUIRED", "SHALL", "SHALL NOT", "SHOULD", "SHOULD NOT", "RECOMMENDED", "MAY", and "OPTIONAL" in this document are to be interpreted as described in RFC 2119 [RFC2119].


.ti 0
2.  Document Definition

An RFB document is broken down into four, distinct, and REQUIRED sections outline below.

.ti 0
2.1  Front Page

An overly verbose front-page that MAY contain a wordy introduction to the disputed matter.

The required sections are the Abstract, Status of this Memo, Copyright Notice, and Table of Contents.

The abstract is an attempt to convey the subjective issue to the layperson, single handedly demonstrating the hilarity and insignificance of the dispute. As a result, the abstract should render the rest of the RFB unnecessary.

The memo status summarizes to whom this document is for.

The copyright notice is REQUIRED as The Bikeshed Authority is insanely jealous and wants credit for everything it may possibly have a hand in; Then rub your nose in it.

.bp
.ti 0
2.2  Grievances

The section is comprised of everyone's supposed grievances. The body MAY be an entire waste of your time to read and involves waxed poetics of everyone's opinion.

.ti 0
2.3  Proposed Solutions

This section is considered the most dangerous for perpetuating a "bikeshedded" topic. Members within the Hacklab community propose solutions that either are in direct violation of a previous RFB or spur off an endless cycle of comments, eventually causing all original parties to "drop" the issue.

.ti 0
2.4  RFB Responses

An RFB MAY be written to respond to an existing RFB, increasing the "bikeshedding" factor of the RFB series.


.ti 0
3  RFB Archive

The RFB series is considered an archived series. All Request For Bikeshed memos will be saved permanently by The Bikeshed Authority on its GitHub account:

.ti 6
https://www.github.com/TheBikeshedAuthority/request-for-bikeshed

A member of the Hacklab community, upon writing a valid RFB, MUST make a Pull Request to The Bikeshed Authority to include the RFB into the archive. The Bikeshed Authority will review the proposed RFB and MAY publish it using its sole discretion.

.ti 0
4  Closing Remarks

The Bikeshed Authority invites all members within the Hacklab community to respond to this RFB using the RFB format, and to open all grievances using the new RFB protocol.

This RFB was drafted using NroffEdit, and The Bikeshed Authority encourages writers to use this software to keep them from pulling their hair out when conforming to the formatting standards for RFB.

Good hunting.

.bp
